<1@> Wavelength of light

The wavelength of light is the distance between two consecutive peaks or troughs of a light wave. It is measured in nanometers (nm), which are one billionth of a meter.

The wavelength of light determines its color. Visible light has a wavelength range of approximately 400 nm (violet) to 700 nm (red). Ultraviolet light has a shorter wavelength than visible light, and infrared light has a longer wavelength.

The wavelength of light also determines its energy. High-energy light, such as ultraviolet light, can damage DNA and cause sunburn. Low-energy light, such as infrared light, can be used to heat objects.

The wavelength of light also affects how it interacts with matter. For example, shorter wavelengths of light are scattered more by water molecules, which is why the ocean appears blue.

The wavelength of light is an important property of light that has many applications in science and technology. For example, the wavelength of light is used to select specific colors of light for lasers and other optical devices. The wavelength of light is also used to measure the temperature of objects and to detect different types of atoms and molecules.

Here are some examples of the wavelengths of different types of light:

* Visible light: 400-700 nm
* Ultraviolet light: 100-400 nm
* Infrared light: 700 nm-1 mm
* Microwaves: 1 mm-1 m
* Radio waves: 1 m-1000 km

